## What happened

Apple's security frameworks do not support DSA, and Microsoft has been progressively removing legacy crypto that lacks platform-native backing. In .NET 11, `DSA.Create()` throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** on macOS (and other Apple platforms). It was already marked `[Obsolete]` with diagnostic **SYSLIB0030** in earlier releases — .NET 11 completed the removal.

Windows and Linux still work because Windows CNG and OpenSSL both still expose DSA.

## How to fix it

Since you only need to **verify** existing signatures (not create new ones), you have two options:

### Option 1 – Use BouncyCastle (recommended cross-platform fix)

```csharp
// Install: dotnet add package BouncyCastle.Cryptography
using Org.BouncyCastle.Security;

bool VerifyLegacyDsa(byte[] message, byte[] signature, byte[] publicKeyDer)
{
    var keyParam = PublicKeyFactory.CreateKey(publicKeyDer);
    var verifier = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA1withDSA"); // or SHA256withDSA
    verifier.Init(forSigning: false, keyParam);
    verifier.BlockUpdate(message, 0, message.Length);
    return verifier.VerifySignature(signature);
}
```

This works identically on all three platforms with no native dependency.

### Option 2 – Runtime guard (if Windows/Linux-only is acceptable)

```csharp
if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
{
    using var dsa = DSA.Create();
    // ...
}
else
{
    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
        "Migrate legacy DSA signatures to ECDSA/RSA.");
}
```

### Long-term recommendation

Re-sign or migrate away from DSA entirely — it's considered weak (1024-bit key limits in FIPS 186-2). ECDSA or Ed25519 (via `ECDsa` or .NET's newer `AsymmetricAlgorithm` APIs) are the modern replacements.
